Initially I didn't like it at all, then I gradually got happier with it, but towards the end I thought it absolutely vile. My conclusion is still that this is not a good beer. The best I can say is that it's definitely unusual, and clearly not boring.

Big white fine-laced head, clear copper body. Soft, faintly spicy floral hop aroma. Taste is initially caramel malts, followed by floral hops and apples. Dry, papery, mealy aftertaste with a grassy bitterness is the lowest point of the beer. Not the most exciting Pilsner, but decent. (0.5l can.)

Smallish, normal-laced white head, which subsides quite quickly. Pale copper body with some solitary bubbles floating upwards. Hardly any aroma; can faintly detect some caramel malts, but that's it. Very faint and watery taste; only in the aftertaste can a vague malt and hop taste be detected. Very, very boring.

Big head of fine lace, pale copper body with some ongoing carbonation. Nice aroma of pine-like hops, with notes of metal and grain.  Crisp, clean taste of caramel malts; soft aftertaste of pine-like hops. Not that much taste to this one, but what there is is very clean and nice; for a Norwegian lager this is pretty good.

Biggish creamy white head over pale yellow body. Acidic, refreshing aroma with fruity notes and some grain. Taste is apple-like with some light malts. Aftertaste is very light bitterness with some straw. Not at all bad; in fact, probably the best Norwegian "summer beer". A decent light lager. (0.5l can.)

Biggish, creamy white head with larger bubbles; very pale yellow body with ongoing carbonation. Faint aroma of apple and some noble hops. Taste is more apple, faintly sourish, and very soft aftertaste with slightly metallic hops. One of the better Norwegian pilseners.

Small, white, coarse head; brown body. Faint aroma of roasty caramel and some grain. Grainy, watery taste of caramel and straw, and something else that shouldn't be there. Hardly any aftertaste. Very disappointing. A bayer should taste more than this, and the off flavour is disappointing, too.

Medium, creamy, white head; light bronze body. Aroma of noble hops with notes of grain, straw, and, faintly, apple. Taste of apple and wood, with soft aftertaste of noble hops. For a Norwegian pilsener this is great.

Small, tan, quickly dissipating head. Darkish red body. Light, harmonic sweet aroma with notes of cinnamon and caramel. Arojma could be stronger. Sweet cinnamon taste, with nice, lightly dry aftertaste. Faint roasted notes lingering. A nice christmas beer, if somewhat on the light side.

Small tan head, dissipates quickly. Dark translucent red body. Sweet, dense aroma of caramel and notes of wild berries, with some cinnamon. Broad, very sweet taste of cinnamon and roasted malts, with some caramel. Faint, slightly dry aftertaste with lingering burnt cinnamon taste. Quite good, but perhaps a bit too sweet.

Medium coarse-laced white head; clear straw-yellow body with ongoing carbonation. Sweet aroma of wet straw and faint caramel with metallic hoppy notes. Sweet caramel straw taste; aftertaste has bitter aspects, as well as overtones of earth and metal. Not really very pleasant.

No head (probably because of glass). Brown body with ongoing carbonation. Very faint aroma, hard to detect what is there. Strong taste of roasted malts, followed by powerful hop aroma. Aftertaste is dry and roasty. Not at all bad, with the hops clearly being the best part.

Big beige head of coarse lace on dark red almost opaque body. Sweet harmonic coffee aroma with licorice, pepper, and pine notes. Sweet, smoky, burnt taste; aftertaste is a strange combination of driness, bitterness, soot, and coffee. Strangely thin mouthfeel. The sooty bitterness doesn't really do it for me, but definitely a quality brew.

Tan, creamy head with larger bubbles, deep dark red body. Deep sweet aroma with notes of pepper and coffee and some alcohol. Lovely, sweet, firm taste of wild berries, coffee, and slight sourness. Slightly, oily mouthfeel. Fruity, dry, somewhat bitter, peppery aftertaste. Burnt flavours linger. Excellent, but could do with less of the sourness.

Biggish brown head. Nearly opaque dark brown body. Roasty coffeeish aroma with hoppy oily rye notes. Dry-sweetish taste, with an acidic edge, of burnt sooty rye with vaguely citric hop notes. Very harmonic and balanced. Full-bodied. Soft mouthfeel. Dry delicate burnt aftertaste with grainy chocolatey notes. Burnt notes linger. Very, very good and highly drinkable. Grew on me as I drank. (0.5l bottle, Wine monopoly, Oslo.)

Offwhite, coarse medium head of quickly shrinking foam over slightly hazy light red-brown body. Aroma of lightly roasted malts with notes of wood and traces of citrusy hops. Sourish, oily taste of bitterness. Not that much taste; essentially dominated by the citrusy hops. Lacking in body. Dry aftertaste. Not really up to usual NØ standard.

Offwhite, creamy medium head with larger bubbles. Hazy pale orange-red body with ongoing carbonation. Eccentric aroma that is a harmonic vinuous blend of caramel and earth. Sourish metal taste with some bitterness and notes of stale hops. Slightly watery. Aftertaste simply disappears. Refreshing, but I have to admit that this is a world classic I don't really enjoy that much.

Medium white head, quickly subsiding. Clear orange body. Sweet vinuous banana-like aroma with sourish lacquer notes. Taste very like the aroma, very soft. Watery mouthfeel. Faint, lingering, peppery, banana-like flavours. No real aftertaste. Good, highly drinkable, but for a Belgian-style beer not that interesting.
Small, tan, creamy head; black opaque body. Faint, roasty aroma. Deep, sweet, roasty taste, leading to an aftertaste of coffee and licorice. Very harmonic and balanced; not too complex. Great!

Tan creamy medium head with some larger bubbles. Black opaque body. Sweet aroma with notes of coffee. Deep, sweet taste of cocos with notes of bitter chocolate with dry cocos aftertaste. Lots of taste, but the chocolate really makes it very unpleasant for me. Really did not enjoy this, even if it has lots of taste.

Medium, creamy, white head with larger bubbles. Clear brown body. Faint nutty aroma. Sweet, nutty taste with resiny, citrusy hop notes. Soft, dry aftertaste with notes of resin and pine needles. Quite drinkable, but nothing special.

Medium, creamy, white head with larger bubbles over clear yellow body. Thin hop aroma. Taste of sourish malts with resiny hops and softly bitter aftertaste. Pine needles. Quite good, highly drinkable.

Offwhite creamy head of medium size with larger bubbles over dark red body. Sweet aroma of anis. Sweet malty taste with overpowering cocos flavour. Quite bitter. Dry, sharp aftertaste of cocos. Interesting, but mostly a novelty beer.

Medium creamy white head over light brown clear body. Aroma of citrusy pine hops so harmoniously blended with sweet caramel malts that the two can hardly be told apart. Deep, sweet, malty taste of nuts, combined with bitterness, citrus, and pine needles. Soft, bitter aftertaste. Glorious! World class! It's really the EKG hops that make this one.

Thin, coarse-laced white head on light brown body. Faint sourish aroma of resin and pine and green peas. Sweetish, light, clean taste of resin and pine, with a soft, dry finish. Very drinkable, quite good. (Cask at the Britannia.)

Thin, coarse-laced off-white head on dark red body. Faint sourish aroma of nuts and faint sweet roastiness. Taste is smooth, clean, nutty maltiness; quite bitter. Aftertaste is drily nutty, with hoppy bitterness lingering. Clearly a well-made beer, but rather subdued. (Cask at the Britannia.)

Thin, coarse-laced head; dark brown body. Faint sourish aroma. Taste much like aroma: bitter, sourish, thin. Dry aftertaste, with lingering pine needles. Some wood. Not at all bad, but a little boring. (On cask at the Anglesea Arms.)
Thin, coarse-laced head; clear brown body. No carbonation. No aroma to speak of. Soft, sourish taste of hops, dry finish. Not very remarkable. Bitterness lingers. (Cask at the Anglesea Arms.)

Small, offwhite head; brown body. Nutty, earthy aroma, with sweetish malt notes. Powerfully nutty taste, quite bitter. Ends in dry, sharp aftertaste. Roasty, pine needle notes linger. Nice, although a bit one-dimensional, and perhaps a bit too agressive for the lack of complexity. (Bottle.)

Beer: Harveys Imperial Extra Double Stout / Imperial Russian Stout
Comments: Tiny dark brown head; black opaque body. Smell of blueberries, burnt licorice, and sourness. Taste is like aroma, but overpowering. Sticks to the inside of the mouth. Aftertaste dry, lingering version of same. Very good, but could be more complex. (2001 vintage sampled Dec 2005.)

No head; clear brown body. Strong harmonic aroma of lacquer and sherry. Strong taste of fruit, perhaps apple, and port. No aftertaste to speak of. Slight bitterness. Very nice. One to sip. (On bottle.)

Smallish, creamy, offwhite head; dark red-brown body. Faint, sourish, smoky aroma. Thin, sourish taste with smoky notes and some roastiness. Some tanginess, some bitterness. Slightly dry aftertaste. Good, but not outstanding. (Strange; I've been much more excited by this before.) (On tap at White Horse.)

Thin, coarse, white head; clear red-brown body. No discernible aroma. Mild, malty taste, very clean; bitter, but not too much so. Aftertaste rather dry, with citrusy/piney notes of hop (EKG?). Some sweetness. Light, drinkable, and not too boring. (On tap at White Horse.)

Smallish tan creamy head; opaque black body. Aroma so faint I can’t pick anything up. Dense, burnt, coffee-ish, bitter taste. Very harmonic. Faintly sourish. Taste subdued, yet complex. Very nice, and very drinkable, if not the most exciting stout I’ve had. (On tap at Cittie of Yorke.)

Medium tan head; clear dark golden body. Faint, sweet malty aroma of malts, with notes of noble hops. Sweet caramel malt taste with a heavy accent on the malts. Slightly roasted malty taste; the roastiness becomes more noticeable in the aftertaste, which is quite bitter for a mass-market lager. Some noble hop aroma, but not much. Less boring, and with more body than the usual mass-market lagers. Faintly off taste lingering in the bitterness. Overall this is OK. Improves greatly as it warms.

Huge, offwhite, creamy head; clear, brown body with ongoing carbonation. Faint, harmonic aroma of resiny hops and some malts, maybe some bready notes. Taste is extremely smooth, of slightly roasted, faintly smoky malts, with a lovely, crisp aftertaste of resiny hops, and maybe some citrus hops. The taste is very balanced, and nice. Some bitterness. Not the most complex, or fancy-tasting beer I've had, but exceptionally well made, and highly drinkable. Highly recommended!

Tan medium head, dark red body. Faint malty aroma with notes of roastiness. Taste is quite strong, but is mostly malty caramel taste, with some sweetness. Carbonation disturbs the tasting somewhat. Watery mouthfeel. Aftertaste is dry, and the combination of bitterness and roastiness has some buttery notes to it that are quite unpleasant. Didn't like this one much.

Medium white creamy head; light red body with ongoing carbonation. Light, fruity aroma, mild malts. Malty sweet caramel taste, quite light and clean, but not at all weak. A bit light on the malts for a Christmas beer, perhaps. Faint, dry aftertaste with peppery feel. Nice, but not that interesting.

Beer: Les Frères Houblon Fontaine du Diable
Comments: Huge, tan head; deep dark red body, seems clear. Weak aroma of roasted malts with faint buttery notes, some sweetness and licorice. Smoky taste that is quite sour, but doesn't seem off. Aftertaste is mostly smokiness and roasted flavour. Buttery notes and mouthfeel. Well. Not that great, but not bad, either. Grew on me as I went through the bottle (so the overall went from 12 to 13). The sourness takes some getting used to. Not sure what style this is meant to be.

Offwhite, smallish head; hazy red body. Sweet, spicy aroma of paradise seeds, stale hops, and bread, with something sharp in it. Sharp taste of paradise seeds and citrusy hops, faint roasty notes. Citrusy hops and bitterness make up the van. Quite good, but too much yeast, not enough balance, and not enough complexity.

Medium off-white head of large bubbles; clear, dark red body. Sweet malty aroma, notes of bread; faint notes of coffee. Not that much aroma. Sweet taste, with some off notes, maybe some butter. Faint bitterness, faint burntess. Not very much taste, and some of what is there isn’t entirely right. Well. It’s OK, I guess. A disappointment, this, as some of the other Mack stuff is quite good.

Big tan, creamy head; clear dark red body. Tight, not too strong, harmonic aroma of chocolate, some coffee, and, treacle. Deep and firm taste of sweet malts, notes of chocolate and coffee, maybe burnt bread. Almost oily mouthfeel. Very nice lightly burnt aftertaste lingers on. Taste is as harmonic as the aroma. Very good, if a bit mild. This has to be easily the best Norwegian bock.

Tan, creamy head with lots of larger bubbles; deep dark red body, almost like red wine. Malty, bready aroma with some light burnt, coffeeish notes, some licorice, hops also faintly noticeable, but can't tell what kind. Very harmonic aroma. Taste is very like the aroma, round and slightly watery. In the aftertaste the burntness becomes much more pronounced. Aftertaste also slightly dry, with a peppery feel to it. There is hops here, but hard to detect. Very harmonic. Overall, an excellent traditional Norwegian Christmas beer, but a little bit too weak. Had it been more assertive this would have been a real winner for this style.

Big, creamy yet big-bubbled tan head; clear, dark red body. Aroma mostly citrusy hops and clean, firm malts. Taste is bitter and firm, with a roasty taste that has smoky notes in it. Some dried fruit. Quite bitter throughout, in fact, almost dry.  Very harmonic. Aftertaste is mostly fading, but roasty/smoky flavour lingers. Very nice.

Biggish head of coarse white lace atop clear pale golden body. Aroma is thin and faint, consisting mostly of grass notes plus some hints of noble hops and pale malts. Taste is rounded pale malts with more grassy notes and perhaps some slight apple hints. Aftertaste is a combination of grain soup and metal. Bitter throughout. Why all this bitterness (the Hansa trademark) with no hop aroma? I'd happily trade all the bitterness for an equal dose of aroma. Not very good this, even there's really little actively wrong with it.

Deep, dark, hazy body; small tan head. Deep aroma of citrusy hops, with sweet malt character, somewhat oily. Aroma not too powerful. Taste is bitter, oily, citrusy, sweet, deep and firm, with faint caramel malts. Oily, carbonated mouthfeel. Unusually deep and powerful taste for an IPA. Very good!

Tan, creamy, biggish head with larger bubbles. Black, opaque body, dark brown at edges. Deep, firm aroma of coffee, noble hops, licorice, and some chocolate. Soft, firm, creamy taste of coffee, roasted malts, noble hops, licorice, chocolate. Very complex. Aftertaste is (again) burnt coffee and hops. Extremely good! Wow! All hail!

Medium tan head doesn't last. Nearly opaque black body goes dark brown at edges with floaties and carbonation. Roasty coffee and toffee aroma with earthy licorice notes. Dry-sweet earthy chocolatey taste with funky, faintly acidic notes. Mid-bodied. Mild, soft, smooth mouthfeel with faint heat. Dry funky earthy chocolate aftertaste with coffee and earth notes. Some alcohol, too, and a kind of strawberry chewing gum character. Quite nice and well made. Harmonic and drinkable. (0.33l bottle, wine monopoly, Vika, Oslo.)

Creamy, offwhite medium head, clear orange body. Light aroma of citrusy hops with hints of pine needles. Deep firm taste of hops (citrusy, pine-like, some resin) and sweet caramel malts. Long, lingering aftertaste of hops. Broad, firm body, oily mouthfeel. Hard to separate out all the tastes here. Excellent IPA! Low on aroma, but high on taste.

Brown, creamy head with larger bubbles. Black opaque body, possibly slightly brown at the edges. Faint aroma of chocolate and coffee. Sweet, firm taste with smoky notes, rather soft round the edges. Somewhat mild for an imperial stout, even a little watery. No real aftertaste, just dries up. Coffee notes linger. A good imperial stout, but not among the best.

Beer: Stoudts Fat Dog Stout (Vintages 2004 and later)
Comments: Dark, chocolate brown creamy head with large bubbles. Body black, totally opaque. Harmonic aroma with chocolate and coffee, quite sweet, some hops. Not too powerful. Smooth, coffee taste, with peppery notes. Aftertaste is more roast coffee and driness. Impressively smooth and harmonic for a beer this powerful, but perhaps slightly boring.

Tan, creamy, medium head. Clear brown body with a red tinge to it. Aroma very like sherry with hop notes; firm and sweet. Deep, sweet, complex taste of caramel and sherry with coffee and licorice notes, quite bitter throughout. Round, oily mouthfeel. Aftertaste is bitter and roasty. Some alcohol heat. Lingers in the mouth. Excellent! Have put one in the cellar; really looking forward to tasting it in a few years.

Medium white head, deep orange-brown hazy body. Deep malty aroma with notes of banana and other fruits (dates?). Taste also has lots of banana, with other fruits thrown in, possibly some raisin, definitely some apple. Nice malts throughout. Aftertaste is faintly bitter, like grapefruit. Very nice, although not very Christmasy by Norwegian standards.

Big, offwhite, somewhat creamy head; deep dark red body. Sweet malty aroma with notes of straw- or grass-like hops. Taste is full of sweet malts initially, followed by sweet, caramel and chocolate malts, and relatively mild grassy hops. Overall, an OK beer. Ok for Christmas, ok for any other time. Not that interesting.

Offwhite head; red-brown body. Deep licorice aroma with notes of malts, corn and overwhelming anise. Aroma certainly is interesting, if not that good. Taste is initially only bitter, but quickly followed by a deep chocolate and anise flavour. Aftertaste is dry, followed by nothing. Well. A different beer, that’s for sure, but not that good, or even interesting. I see that this is Ringnes’s attempt to do something different, but they could have tried a lot of things more interesting (or better!) than this.

Poured so carefully by the host that it had no head; deep dark wine-red body. Deep, firm, sweet, chocolate, toffee and coffee aroma. Almost too sweet. Deep, sweet (again, I know) taste, of burnt, toffee, with chocolate overtones. Faintly watery. Fades into lingering burntness, with lots of coffee. Very nice, although too sweet, and perhaps too clinging, for a proper porter. In the end, this is quite good.

Big creamy head, cloudy dirty orange body. Lovely, firm aroma of licorice (?) with a faintly sourish tinge to it. Recognize the taste as typically Belgian, even if I struggle to describe it. Taste is likewise deep and very powerful, quite spicy, and aftertaste is likewise spicy. Paradise seeds? Probably coriander. Lots of hops in the taste, but can't recognize what variety. Too much carbonation, unfortunately. Very good Belgian, even if slightly one-dimensional.

Tan, biggish head; dark red-brown body. Sweet malty aroma with winey notes, faint chocolate, and some bread. Taste also sweet, but with a lot more roastiness, some chocolate, maybe anise? Faintly dry aftertaste. Very good, if perhaps slightly watery.

Normall, smallish head; clear, copper body. I don't know what ninkeberry is, but this has a lovely, strong aroma of it. Sweet, fruity, very slightly tart. Taste is much like the aroma, with only a faint off tone in it. A little watery. No aftertaste to speak of. Lovely fruit beer.

Offwhite medium head of coarse lace on copper-brown body. Faint floral hop aroma together with some caramel and hops. Malty taste with a little sweetness and quite a bit of caramel, together with faint hop notes and a little metal. Aftertaste is mostly a lingering hop/metal flavour  in the mouth. Well. Not much of anything here. Certainly doesn't remind me of Christmas in any way. Definitely prefer the normal Clausthaler over this.

Medium head of coarse white lace sits atop clear, light copper-toned body. Aroma is mostly floral hops, with notes of grass and perhaps a bit of clean straw. Taste is much like the aroma, very light initially, but with some straw/caramel malts. Ends in a nice, crisp, slightly dry bitterness. Very good for a non-alcoholic beer!

Huge offwhite head; cloudy dark mud-orange body with ongoing carbonation. Subtle aroma of sweetness, and possibly some spices. Not really that much aroma. Taste is mellow, clean, light, and ends in a faintly dry aftertaste with some faintly spicy notes. Mouthfeel slightly muddy. Well. This was kind of boring, if you ask me.

Brownish, large, creamy head; black near-opaque body, with dark red visible through thinner parts of glass. Sweet aroma of pine needles, cloves, coffee, pepper, and who knows what else. Surprisingly harmonic aroma. Taste is more subdued, surprisingly, and equally harmonic (unlike last year's, I seem to recall). Coffee, citrusy hops, roasted malts, and cloves can be made out. A peppery roastiness lingers. Lovely! Definitely this year's Christmas beer!

Large, creamy, tan head; dark red visible through the body with some difficulty. Aroma is sweet maltiness with some hops, relatively faint. (How on earth did they brew this to 9.9%, with huge gravity, and leave no aroma? If done on purpose it requires uncommon skill, and a pretty perverse mind.) Taste is deep, round, and sweet, with notes of chocolate, coffee, and cloves. Aftertaste is dry, roasty and full of cloves and other spices. Very good. The best beer ever produced under the Ringnes label by a very long stretch.

Big, creamy, off-white head; black opaque body going brownish round the edges. Subdued sweetish toffee aroma with hints of chocolate, coffee, and citrusy hops. Deep, sweet coffee taste, well rounded, ending in a nicely rounded dry, roasty aftertaste. Strong notes of citrusy hops run underneath the taste from start to finish, and is a nice contribution. Taste not that powerful, but deep and lovely. An excellent Christmas beer.

Huge, offwhite head over clear dark ruby body. Aroma is strong, and cool, full of sweetness, stale hops, coriander, and other spices. Taste is clean and light, initially, but quickly gives way to spices (pepper, cinnamon, and who knows what else), but the mouthfeel is a little watery (possibly because of what I had before this beer). Faintly reminiscent of wine, also has some lingering burntness. Overall a good Belgian.

Huge dark, tan, creamy head with some large bubbles; opaque black body. Sweet aroma with vanilla and touches of pine needles. Taste is dense and firm, with more vanilla (quite dominant, in fact), pine needles, and touches of coffee. Aftertaste is lingering driness, roastiness, and spice. Very interesting, and definitely well made,  thought I don't much care for the vanilla.

Tan coarse-laced medium head topping opaque black body. Aroma of coffee and citrusy hops. Powerful, sweet, roasty taste with notes of hops, and a nicely rounded burnt dry finish. Lovely! Now this is a proper Christmas beer. (This rating stinks. Need to rerate.)

Medium off-white head; clear mahogany body. Sweet malty aroma with notes of chocolate, bread, and alcohol. Nice, mellow, rounded taste of faintly musty sweet malts, ending in an aftertaste consisting mostly of spice (cinnamon?). A well-rounded Christmas beer, but not really very exciting.

Medium white lace over clear golden body; looks like your normal pilsener. Good aroma of light malts, flower hops, and slight metal notes. Smells like your normal German pilsener, too. Sweet, clean, malty taste with hoppy undertones ending in a faintly dry finish. Overall pretty boring, with the hops being the best thing about it. Not a Christmas beer by Norwegian standards, but not a pilsener, either.
Big, coarse, white head; clear, copper-yellow body. Faint aroma of citrusy hops. Taste is clean and light, dominated by the citrus hops, with a a clear, bitter finish. An okay ale.

Small, white, coarse head; orange body with some haziness. Aroma is lovely citrusy hops. Taste is quite bitter, and dominated by the same citrusy hops. Finish is quite dry, and the bitterness lingers in the mouth. A decent pale ale; the hops are the best part, and in fact the only one I can make out.

Clear, copper body with some ongoing carbonation. Virtually no head. Thin, cool, malt aroma with faint floral hops. Taste is clean and light, with some caramel malts, and a faintly dry finish that has a nice, floral hop profile. The hops are the best thing about this beer, which is otherwise wholly unremarkable.

Medium white head; pale yellow body. Faint aroma of floral hops and pale pilsener malts. Faint, but quite nice. Taste is very light and clean, with a very nicely complementing aftertaste that is faintly dry with floral hops. Some very faint metal in the aftertaste. A good pilsener, but could be a bit more assertive. (0.33l bottle.)

Medium head of white, coarse lace; clear, yellow body. Aroma of nice floral hops with some notes of straw and metal. This, mostly clean taste, with lots of hops and some caramel, straw, and water. Nicely dry finish. Excellent for a non-alcoholic beer. For a pilsener it's decent, but with too little malts.

Big light beige creamy head with coarse lace in the middle. Body is deep red. Sickly sweet unbalanced aroma of malts, cinnamon, chocolate, and wet cardboard with buttery notes. Taste is buttery straw with roasty caramel notes and a bitter cardboard aftertaste. (0.33l bottle. Also rated it much more positively late Nov 2005. Did rating over again now, without looking at previous rating.)

Medium, white coarse-laced head atop yellow copper body. Powerful hop aroma with some straw notes; not too nice. Taste is thin grain soup  with light hop notes in the finish. No bitterness. Why make this? If I wanted to stay sober I’d rather drink water.

Deep dark red-brown body under creamy tan head. Deep, dense, sweet aroma with notes of coffee, and perhaps a little butter? Taste is rather like the aroma, but sweeter, and with more of the butter. Hardly any aftertaste. Strange that they should bother storing the beer only to end up with this. Points for effort, but minus for the result. (Need to retaste this one; if gr0ve likes it this much, maybe the glass was polluted by the previous beer (Tuborg juleøl)).

White, smallish coarse-laced head; clear copper body. Doesn't look like a Christmas beer to me. Strange, nutty aroma that seems slightly off. Taste is no better, really. Quite hoppy, but nothing much else is detectable, except some ugly buttery notes. Aftertaste is also poor. Not sure why I bother describing it this carefully. Surely this particular bottle must be off? It can't really be this bad, can it? Hard to see how this stuff would do anyone any good, Tuborg included.

Small, tan, normal-laced head; clear, dark red watery-looking body. Strong, sweet aroma with quite a bit of coffee. Taste is quite firm and sweet, but a little watery; aftertaste has some hops and some faint coffee notes. Too watery, but otherwise quite good. If they firmed it up this would be very good.

Smallish, offwhite head, clear dark red body. Sweet cinnamon malt aroma with some peppery hints to it and some hop notes. Taste is cleanly malty and lightly burnt, slightly watery, with a soft, faintly dry aftertaste. Another light, clean Christmas beer without much taste.

Biggish, tan, creamy head, subsiding quickly; clear red-brown body. Compact aroma with prominent roastiness and hints of spice, almost vinous. Deep, firm taste of malts with some roast, and a clear, dry aftertaste. Among the better Christmas beers this year.

Medium white creamy head; clear chestnut brown body. Aroma of sweet malts and some hops, with hints of roastiness. Taste is clean, light and sweet, faintly watery, with some maltiness and faint roastiness. Aftertaste is pretty faint. A well-made beer, having nothing wrong with it, but definitely intended to please the Norwegian market by tasting as little as a Christmas beer could possibly get away with.

Coarse-laced tan medium head; clear, dark red body. Sweet, malty aroma, not too strong, with hints of licorice. Soft, malty taste with a strange tangy edge to it. Aftertaste is faintly bitter and quite rounded, with some roastiness. An OK Christmas beer, but not really that interesting.

Tan, smallish head, creamy head with large bubbles, subsides quickly. Clear, dark winy red body. Aroma is entirely cinnamon and cloves, and some water. Not really that pleasant. Taste is like the aroma, but with rather more roastiness. No real aftertaste, unfortunately. Well. The idea of a spiced beer is good, but the beer itself is only OK.

Medium, creamy, tan head with a spattering of larger bubbles; clear, dark winy red body. Sweet aroma of syrup, cinnamon, and some roast malts. Aroma is quite thick and satisfying. Roasty taste, with a dry finish, which lingers in the mouth, together with the roastiness.  On further acquaintance, a bit watery. A good Christmas beer; could use a bit more sharpness, but a good effort. Certainly better than expected. (0.33l bottle.)

Medium creamy off-white head; clear dark wine-red body. Sweet aroma of chocolate and bread. Sweet, treacly taste, somewhat watery, yet very clear. Ends in a faintly aftertaste with very faint hop hints. Not at all bad, but a little weak and boring.

Medium white head. Yellow body with carbonation. Grassy musty rubbery aroma . Dry-sweetish salty grassy papery taste with mineraly floral notes. Mid-bodied. Dusty mouthfeel. Dry minty metallic aftertaste with floral papery notes. It's OK, but bland, and generally mixes good elements with bad. (0.33l bottle, Systembolaget, Charlottenberg.)

Thin, white head over hazy honey-coloured body. Deep aroma of peach with sharper, more acidic notes. Lovely taste combining peach and gueuze-like flavours with a dry, slightly stale finish. Very good.

Big, offwhite, creamy head with large bubbles; body clear dark red. Deep aroma of caramel, bread, and spice.  Taste is broad and sweet, with some alcohol heat, settling into an aftertaste with faint roastiness and lots of spice. Licorice. Nice balancing aftertaste, which lingers. Excellent! One of the best beers made.

Huge, coarse, off-white head; dull, brown hazy body. Sweet, cinnamon, bready aroma, with thin estery notes to it. Lovely, sweet, rounded taste of caramel, honey and yeast, which ends in a nice bitter finish that somehow merges with the sweetness. An excellent, and very unusual, tripel.

Medium, white normally laced head.; clear pale golden body. Faint hop aroma. Taste is clean and light, with a nice crisp edge to the aftertaste, and a definite saaz aroma. Very nice. Worthy, in fact, of a German brewery. (Not so strange, perhaps, given that Ludwig Mack *was* German.)

Big, offwhite coarse-laced head; clear light brown body. Caramel malt aroma with hop hints. Taste is surprisingly fruity, mostly dominated by a very nice hop profile, and caramel malt tones. Aftertaste is nicely rounded and bitter, if somewhat subdued. Much better than expected. Somewhat light, but still a very good dark lager. It’s the aroma hops that really make this beer.

Pale golden body under rapidly subsiding head of coarse white lace. Faint aroma of malt and crisp hops. Clean malty taste with hints of straw; clean crisp bitter hop finish. A very well-made pilsner, though not that exciting. Certainly not the best pilsner I’ve had.

Tan-pink creamy head with large bubbles in; body is opaque drab red. Aroma is sharp raspberry with hints of sourness. Taste is subtle raspberry with unidentifiable notes and a sharp edge. Aftertaste is quite dry. Sourish. Well, not bad, but not that exciting, either. (0.33l bottle. 2002 vintage sampled in 2005.)

Milky brown body settles into medium beige creamy head, sharply separated from the nearly opaque but in fact deep dark red translucent body. Milky vaguely caramelly and chocolatey aroma with faint metallic notes. Dry-sweetish roasty metallic caramel taste. Mid-bodied. Mild, soft mouthfeel. Dry milky metallic aftertaste with vague burnt notes. Fairly bland, but easy to drink, and no real off tastes other than the metal. (0.5l can, Rema, Lillestrøm. Second rating. Initial rating from 2005 was much too positive.)

Initially milky body, but gradually settles into a clear dark chestnut brown under a creamy off-white medium head. Looks lovely. Very faint aroma of sweet caramelly malts. Taste is clean and light, quite sweet, notes of licorice and treacle. It gives way to a faintly bitter aftertaste, with a vague hop taste. Very mild, and not really very interesting. (From can.)

Medium white coarse-laced head; clear, pale yellow body. Faint, watery aroma with some caramel and hops. Taste is light and sweetish with a bit of caramel and a vague, slightly unpleasant hop finish. At best boring, at worst a little off-putting. Starts off ok, goes all bland and boring, then takes a definite dive in the finish. Lacks any form of "bite".

Small, tan head with coarse lace over clear dark brown body. Aroma is light and sweet; not very strong. Taste is clean, light, not too powerful. Malty, with quite a bit of roastiness; roastiness grows more pronounced in aftertaste, which also has nice, rounded bitterness. A well-made beer, but not very exciting.

Small, normal-laced head over clear copper body. Aroma is nearly non-existent. Taste is likewise extremely light, before some slight bitterness and hop aroma emerges in the aftertaste. Well, this has to win the prize for least-tasting beer ever.

Clear, pale yellow body under a small, white, normal-laced head. Aroma is very faint and hard to place. Mostly stale apple, I'd say. Taste has more body to it than the other two in this series I've tried, but the same cleanness. Taste is mostly very light malts, followed by a nice, crisp bitterness. Not much to this, but nothing wrong with it, either. Best thing about it is probably the aftertaste.

Medium coarse-laced white head, which quickly subsides completely. Clear copper body. Powerful aroma of straw and some caramel. Taste is a mix of straw and watery grain soup. Aftertaste has some bitterness, but hardly any aroma, as if they've only put in used hops. This is just piss poor. Probably the worst beer I've ever tasted (provided we except ones that had gone bad).

Biggish white creamy head specked with larger bubbles topping clear copper body. Faint aroma of caramel-like malts and grain with a hint of hops. Taste is all grain, cereal and some straw, with very slight roastiness. Watery mouthfeel. Aftertaste has hints of hops and bitterness, but is mostly watered-out grain. This is pretty poor, if not really unpleasant. Why not dump in some hops to give it some taste and hide the worst? Too expensive, probably.

Medium white normal-laced head over clear yellow body. Faintly floral aroma with hints of something I can't quite place, maybe a bit sourish. Taste is clean, light, and slightly malty, but quickly overpowered by a nice floral hop aftertaste with only slight bitterness. Very light aftertaste. Much lighter than in the 318. Of the two I've tasted so far, this is clearly the least interesting.

Huge, white coarse head over a clear light yellow body. Aroma is light, clean, faintly sweet, and faintly hoppy. Little malts in the aroma, it's more floral. Taste is very light initially with faint maltiness and hints of sweetness, then quite hoppy and bitter in the aftertaste. Very well balanced, and extremely clean, but not much character. Lovely hop profile in aftertaste.

Small, tan, normal-laced head, reddish brown body. Very faint aroma of sweet malts. Unusual taste of light roastiness, with aftertaste somewhat like smoked toffee. Very sweet, with a taste that lingers. Smooth at first, then roasty. Very strange; never had anything quite like it. Relatively light mouthfeel; taste not too strong. Good, and very interesting.

Small, fine-laced head, clear yellow body, neither light nor dark. Clean malt aroma with hints of hops. Taste is rather like the aroma, but more grainy, somewhat stale, and with metal hints in the rather dry aftertaste. Palate is clean, but very watery. Overall a very light beer, without much taste, but not entirely without faults. A half-decent pilsener.

Creamy, white head with a spattering of large darkish bubbles, over opaque dirty yellow body. Aroma is pretty faint, but citrusy and spicy. Taste is light, mouthfeel marked by carbonation hiding most of what is initially going on, leaving a light citrusy taste with notes of something else (probably coriander). Overall, a light, clean, refreshing beer, but ot the greatest of beer experiences, perhaps. It feels strange to criticize such an established world classic, but the fact is that there are better witbiers around (the other Hoegaardens being the prime examples of this).

Dark, clear, red-brown body under a medium tan normal-laced head. Light dry roasty aroma. Taste is rather like the aroma, but has a metallic tinge. Dry, metallic aftertaste. Not much taste to this one, and a bit thin. Typical German schwarzes, really. (0.5l bottle.)

Medium creamy whitish head, which subsides quickly, over dark red-brown clear body. Aroma of caramel and perhaps some bread.  Strong taste of caramel with notes of burntness; the taste fades towards the end, leaving a taste somewhat like burnt breakfast cereal with some bitterness. Very clean and smooth. A highly drinkable beer, but one with some character. (0.5l bottle.)

Medium creamy white head with some big bubbles, which subsides quickly.  Milky orange body.  Aroma is sourish with notes of flour and maybe a hint of coriander.  Taste is big, with a citrus-like sourness which balances in the mouth. Aftertaste is thin, lingering sourness. A very unusual beer, and a lot more drinkable than the description of the beer type would have you think. I quite like it, without really thinking it the greatest invention of the beer world.

Biggish white medium-laced head, light copper, clear body. Light, grainy aroma, with some metal notes and pilsener hops. Palate none too smooth; mostly grainy taste with some off notes. Well. It's a pilsener. It's drinkable. It doesn't really stand out in any way, though. (0.5l can.)

Medium white creamy head sites nicely atop clear straw yellow body, with constant carbonation. Faint aroma of hops and maybe some straw. Clean, soft, and smooth mouthfeel. When cold it's terribly boring; when warmer there's still hardly any malt taste, but quite a powerful hop taste, and quite bitter. Quite a good pilsener. Very nice edge to the bitterness, which balances nicely on the tongue. A subtle beer; quite good.

Biggish white coarse head, clear, pale yellow body. Aroma is relatively faint (on an airplane, at least), mostly pilsner hops. Very clean and smooth mouthfeel with little taste; aftertaste is a lovely rounded bitterness, with strong hop notes. Very bitter for a pilsener. For a pilsener this is not bad at all, but perhaps a bit too much metal in the aftertaste. (0.33l bottle.)

Big, tan, coarse-laced head which quickly subsides. Body is dark brown-red, nearly opaque. Carbonation keeps going on. If you pour in the yeast sediment you can enjoy watching yeast balls sinking, then getting caught by bubble streamers and being carried up, then being dropped at the top and starting over. (Or not, if you find yeast unappetizing. :) Aroma is yeasty, sweet, peppery, with lots of roastiness. Taste is huge, roasty, and sweet, with an aftertaste of coffee. Very good! This is a great dunkelweizen, though the weizenness of it is not exactly obvious. It's more like a cross with a stout, really. (0.5l bottle.)

A big head of coarse lace atop dark yellow hazy body with bubble streamers. Sweet aroma of wheat malts and banana. Big, round taste of strong banana or chewing gum, with faintly bitter/dry finish. Some faint, refreshing sourness. Very nice and refreshing, with enough taste to make it interesting. Not the top weizen, but good.

Clear yellow body with some yeast particles under a big, creamy head. Strange, subdued hoppy aroma; not sure what kind of hops they used, but have smelt it before. Very nice. The taste is dominated by the same soft, almost salty or stale, hops. Very subtle, and very nice. Never tried anything like this before.

Small, offwhite head, normal lace. Dark wine-red clear body. Earthy aroma of coffee, banana, and compost. Taste is much the same, but roastier, with hints of smoke. Mouthfeel is a little watery. Some caramel. Not really very stout-like, more like a lager my notes say (from both ratings). Not really very good. Flawed. (0.5l bottle, Oslo-Copenhagen ferry.)

Medium coarse-laced white head; clear whiskey-coloured body. Quite big aroma of plums, malts, alcohol and notes of something like cognac.  Taste is light malts, giving way to hops in the finish. Unpleasant metal notes throughout. Not much here. It’s a beer. Some interest in the taste, but not much. Ah well.

Small, offwhite head over dark red-brown clear body. Sweet smell of toffeelike malts. Big, sweet taste of malty, caramelly sweetness, slowly growing bitter towards the end. Good, but doesn't really stand out.

Thin pink coarse-laced head; ruby-red opaque body. Powerful aroma of, well, raspberry; sourish, kind of like a raspberry sauce. Taste is all raspberry, big and round, somewhat stale, growing sharpish towards the end. May sound boring (or like I'm very unimaginative :), but it's actually very nice. Not in the least artificial-tasting, and not so sour you can't enjoy it.

Big white cream head topping wine-red hazy body. Aroma is jelly of wild berries. Big taste that's one great lump of stale hops, old wood, and something musty; aftertaste is mostly bitterness and stale hops. Strangely soft and watery mouthfeel. Really dominated by the hops, but it takes a while to taste it. Good, but not the revelation I'd been led to expect.

Huge, creamy, white head which dwarfs the small orange-yellowish hazy body. (Half of an 0.33l bottle.) Big, fruity aroma of banana and apples with typical Belgian yeast notes. Taste is surprisingly harmonic and subdued compared to the aroma, but is essentially more of the same. Let it stand a little over the best before date, which probably explains the aftertaste being somewhat off. Don't think this is a definitive tasting of this one. It's a good beer, but a little boring, as though something's missing. Not at all what I expected.

Huge, tan, creamy head, almost as big as the opaque black-brown body from half an 0.33l bottle. Aroma has huge caramelly sweetness  with hints of sourness and spice. Initially sweet, round, earthy, almost stale taste gives way to coffee-like roastiness with hints of bitterness, which turns into lingering bitterness and coffee. Mouthfeel is slightly watery. Reminiscent of a moccha coffee. Good, lots of taste, but maybe a little "loose". Could do with more "punch". Also a little too sweet.

Hardly any head; what's there appears to be finely laced. Aroma is quite faint when cold, but has a mix of malts and citrusy hops. Taste is quite big, yet very clean and smooth (extremely harmonic). Again malts and citrusy hops with some metal notes. Metal notes grow stronger when warm. Finish is bitter, but not very. Very nice! A light, highly drinkable, and still interesting IPA. A nice complement to the stronger ones from Nøgne Ø.  (This is also the only IPA approved by my girlfriend, which says something about the drinkability.)

Smallish white coarse-bubbled head atop an opaque black body which is dark brown towards the edges. Aroma is quite faint, some hints of bread and yeast. Taste is dense and hard to make out when cold. Leaving beer to warm up from fridge temperature for some minutes. When warmer: bready, spicy aroma. Still quite faint. Taste is more powerful, very harmonic, but it's hard to make out what it consists of. Not really that interesting. Strong aftertaste of spice, but can't tell which one. Perhaps paradise seeds? Quite bitter, but in a way that doesn't really add to the beer. Not sure what all the fuss over the Westvleteren beers are all about. Rochefort is clearly a lot better.

Huge, creamy white head, which takes forever to subside makes a nice contrast with the dark-orange opaque body. An aroma of yeasty bread hangs around it before I even lift it up to smell properly. Up close it smells more of spicy fruit with the signature de Dolle yeast aroma profile. Powerful, broad taste of bread, coriander, yeast with quite a bit of alcohol heat and a good deal of bitterness at the end. The bitterness is mostly overpowered by the taste, however. Very harmonic, yet complex. An extraordinary beer! Very, very good. Has to be one of the best trippels I've had, mad or sane. (0.33l bottle.)

Medium finely laced head topping a dark wine-red clear body. Aroma is mostly smoke, like smoked sausage minus the sausage. Some malts as well. Taste is sweet malts quickly overpowered by the smokiness, the fading into a smoky smooth bitterness. Aroma is smokier than the taste.  Somehow the smoke makes it feel silkily smooth. Taste settles in the mouth as you drink. A very interesting beer; so interesting, in fact, that drinking it in greater quantities requires some practice. It is more than worth the effort, though. (0.5l bottle. Rerated.)

Largish, coarsely laced head over golden body. Sweet, dense aroma of apples and some hops. Powerful taste of apples, some smokiness, malty sweetness, and a bitter hop finish, with some metal notes. Overall a good ale, but nothing remarkable, and the metal detracts from it a bit. (0.5l bottle.)

Smallish, white head over mahogany-red body. Sweet, malty, earthy, bread-like aroma. Smells somewhat stale, like most German beer. Powerful, sweet taste of malts, very nicely rounded, like marzipan, lingers for a long time in the mouth. An excellent doppelbock.

Big, tan, creamy head, red-black opaque body, with some yeast sediment at the bottom. Subtle aroma of nameless spices, perhaps some anis, perhaps coriander. Very harmonic aroma, and surprisingly subdued. Powerful, dark, spicy taste of malts, coffee, and again spices; very complex, almost burns in the mouth, but still with some harmony. Very dry. Well, what I can say? Beer does not get much better than this. This has to be in the top ten.
Almost no head; deep red-brown colour. Deep cognac-like aroma. Powerful, sourish, sharp taste of dark wood, red wine, and cherry. Very, very good. An excellent Flemish sour ale!

Medium creamy tan head over dark red-brown opaque body, with what appears to be yeast sediment at the bottom. Powerful aroma of sweet cinnamon and cloves with some fruitiness and sharpness. Lovely! Taste is powerful and quite sharp, consisting mostly of malts and the aroma, which grows more pronounced in the aftertaste. Excellent! A great brune!  (0.33l bottle in Orval glass.)

Fine offwhite head over black-orange opaque body. Aroma is faint, but sweetly spicy and malty. Big, sweet toffee-like taste, yet smooth, with some spiciness and complexity. Lingers and settles in the mouth as it fades. Taste grows stronger as you drink more.  (0.5l bottle, served Norwegian fashion, which means too cold and without all the yeast.)

Big tan, creamy head over beautifully dark red/purple body. Aroma of very sweet malts, with notes of syrup and hay. Nice. The taste is again very sweet and malty, but is soon dominated by a smoky hay-like flavour, which lingers and fades. Subtle, yet complex, and very interesting. An excellent lager!  (0.5l bottle in glass.)

Smallish white head, looking somewhat coarse because of the large bubbles. Body is a kind of muddy yellow. Aroma is interesting; kind of thin, and fruity, with strange notes of soap, tea, and something darker. Very powerful taste, with strong notes of what seems like grapefruit; very sour. There are promising things in the taste, but the grapefruit overwhelms it and makes it hard to come to terms with. Didn’t really enjoy this, but the aroma is nice. A beer to smell, but not to drink, I guess is the conclusion.  (0.5l bottle in glass.)  Looking up "agrumes" in a French dictionary I see that it means "citrus fruit". Yeah. That figures.

Big, tan, creamy head over black opaque body. Lots of creamy carbonation in the body that slowly settles into the head, sharply dividing the beer into black body and tan head. Aroma is relatively faint, consisting mostly of roasty maltiness and some metal with some hints of toffee-like sweetness. Taste is deep, roasty treacle leading into a sharply dry finish, which is very bitter, with notes of steel. A good stout, if somewhat light and watery. Overall, it's perhaps a bit brutal without really offering enough in return for the brutality.  (0.5l can in glass.)

Medium white head, dark red-brown body. Aroma is tart and sourish, with hints of smoke. Taste is strongly smoky, almost like rauchbier, with a rounded body, and smoky aftertaste. An interesting beer, and quite good, but not something to drink a lot of.  (0.5l bottle in glass.)

Medium tan head, which quickly subsides, over clear, nutty brown body. Aroma is malts with hints of something nutty and also hops. The taste is quite big and grows to a powerful finish, which is quite bitter. Taste appears to be mostly malts, but the nuttiness is even more pronounced here. A very good beer, and very drinkable.  (0.5l bottle in glass. Unfortunately, now with a modern cork instead of the delightful cap Ruddles used to have.)

Small white head, which quickly disappears, over orange-red body. Lovely, fruity aroma with notes of honey, yeast, and spice. Big, full taste, with grass and fruit notes; very like a normal Belgian trippel. Something odd about it, though, like a slightly off taste. Aftertaste is quite bitter, in fact, maybe too bitter. Overall, a good beer, but certainly far from the best trippel I've had.  (0.65l bottle in glass.)

Medium-sized creamy head, dark-red almost black clear body. Aroma is sweet and raisin-like. Deep, dry toffee/raisin taste, which in the aftertaste dries up. An excellent schwarzbier. Taste could have lingered longer, though. (0.5l bottle.)

Biggish white lasting shiny head. Hazy pale yellow body. Light chalky herbal bananaish aroma. Dryish-sweet bananaish milky pepper taste, soft and rounded, with herbal notes. Full body, mild mouthfeel. Dryish oily banana aftertaste with spicy notes. Light hoppy notes linger. Nice weizen. (0.33l draft at Thüringer Hof, Leipzig. Previously rated at Bäcköfele, Würzburg.)

Arrives in usual stone mug. Nice, creamy head, not too big. Aroma is mostly sweetness with some hops. Big hoppy, meaty, sweet taste. Like a really good IPA, giving way to bitterness and more hops. Very good, and very drinkable. An excellent kellerbier.  (0.5l stone mug.)

Biggish, fine off-white head, dark brown-yellow cloudy body. (Not sure about the colour; it was dark, and the light at the brewery was yellow.) Sweet, toffee-like aroma. Big sweet toffee/licorice taste, with slightly hoppy aftertaste. Complex taste. Aftertaste lingers. A very interesting beer, somewhat heavy by German standards. (0.5l mug on tap at the brewery pub.)

Biggish cream-like white head, which subsides. Cloudy, straw-yellow body. Aroma is weizen-like with banana notes, and something else. Makes me think of ice cream. Round, not too strong, slightly sweet weizen taste, light and pleasant, followed by bitterness, which is sharper than usual for a weizen. Not sure what is so special about this, except possibly the extra bitterness. Overall, a nice, light summer drink, not that special.  (0.33l on tap at the brewery pub.)

Medium finely laced head which barely subsides. Orangle body with continuous carbonation. Lovely hoppy aroma. Broad, deep taste, dominated by aroma-hops, almost like an American IPA. A very good beer, interesting and highly drinkable.   (0.5l mug on tap at the Bruckmayer brewery inn, which claimed they made it. This was 2005-09-01, so maybe things have changed since 2003. Not sure.)  Probably named after the famous Teufelshöhle (devil's cave) just outside Pottenstein.

Medium offwhite head of large bubbles, clear dark red body. Smoky, meaty aroma, not too strong. Taste is deep, but not really strong. I'd be hard-pressed to describe it, but the aftertaste is quite bitter. Overall quite hoppy. A very good example of the Franconian dark lager.  (0.5l mug on tap at the brewery outdoor serving.)

Largish offwhite head, red-brown body. Smoky, hoppy aroma, not too strong. Broad, deep taste with meaty, smoky notes, which culminates nicely, then fades into a nice bitter finish. A good beer, but not too interesting. The smokiness lingers, and grows as you drink. (0.5l mug on tap at the brewery inn.)

Huge head of all equal-sized bubbles, subsides after a while, leaving a column in the middle. Pale yellow body, where carbonation keeps on for a long time. Fine, thin aroma, with strong hop notes. (Girlfriend claims it smells like white wine.) Taste is very light, with a lovely hop finish, which is dry, malty, and rounded. Once white wine has been mentioned it's hard not to taste white wine in it. Very good for a pilsener, mostly because of the hops. (0.5l bottle in Leikeim glasses.)

Big beige head of fine bubbles. Clear dark amber body. Strong, sweet malt aroma, with hints of licorice. Taste is initially dark malts, followed by a strong taste of treacle/licorice with a dry smoky finish. A very good beer, and quite interesting.  (0.5l bottle at the brewery inn.)

Medium fine-bubbled head, dark amber, clear body. Aroma is mostly raisins, with hints of earthiness. Taste is quite powerful and deep, consisting mostly of sweet maltiness and smoky earthiness, with a bitter, dry finish. Something smoky lingers between sips. Overall an unusual dunkel, interesting, and quite good.  (0.5l glass mug on tap at the brewery inn.)

Smallish head, which quickly disappears. Orange cloudy body. Carbonation looks unusual, but I'm hard pressed to describe how. Aroma is faint, but promising; basically like a good weizen with a hint of smokiness. The taste is harmonic, but initially weak. Soon a smoky, fruity taste sets in, which subsides, leaving only the smoke. An unusual weizen, interesting, but not really that good.  (0.5l bottle, self-poured, at the brewery inn.)

Ecological beer made from spelt (German "dinkel") and barley malts, which is highly unusual. The only beer made from spelt I've had, or heard of. 0.33l bottle.  Largish white head, cloudy dark yellow body. Arona is fine and fruity with honey notes. Very reminiscent of weizen with clean estery notes, vaguely watery, and faint crispness in the finish. Drinkable, somewhat watery. Could do with more assertiveness. Faintly sour, without really being refreshing. Doubt I’ll ever drink this again.

Smallish offwhite head which quickly subsides, dark, barely translucent mahogany body. Aroma is fainly sweet and soapy. (Uh? In a dunkel?) Taste is odd, mostly like licorice with notes of metal, malts, and earthiness. An interesting beer, and quite drinkable. Not sure what type this really is; seems to me more like a schwarzbier. (Was called Süffiges Dunkles on the menu, but from Bayreuther Aktien. Hope it's the same beer.)

Tall, white, fine head, pale yellow body; clear, of course. Aroma is faint, but recognizably weizen, with estery, banana-like tones. The taste is clean and light, with fruity tones, which fade out, leaving slight bitterness. Crisp and refreshing, and quite good, but not that interesting. Basically like a superior pilsener. (0.5l on tap.)

Small, thin head, pale yellow colour. Faint aroma, primarily of pilsener and some hops. Light, malty taste, which turns fruity and hoppy towards the end. A good, refreshing pilsener,  which is kind of like a piece of normally good bread: not that exciting. Interesting that they actually brew it in the museum, though.

Medium offwhite head. Slightly hazy brown body with carbonation. Grainy dusty strawy aroma with earthy caramel notes. Dry-sweet grassy grainy dusty taste with strawy earthy notes. Mid-bodied. Mild, soft, clean mouthfeel. Dry grainy toffee and earth aftertaste with caramelly strawy butter notes. Lovely! Extremely drinkable. (0.5l swingtop bottle, Salling, Århus. Also rated in 2005, but that rating was crap, so replaced it.)

Huge, seemingly everlasting head. Mahogany brown body. Aroma faintly sourish (uh?) with hop notes. Taste is subtle, harmonic, and well-rounded, although not too strong. Aftertaste just fades with teasing bitterness notes that last surprisingly long. Reminiscent of many of the Franconian dark lagers I've had, but distinctive, and yet not so interesting. In the typically German way the taste grows stronger as you drink. (On tap at Schinner.)

Fine off-white medium head, impressive black colour, turning black-orange towards the bottom. Aroma is deep and firm with whiffs of chocolate. (Wow! What's this?) Taste is deep, fruity, with overtones of chocolate, and slightly sour towards the end. An excellent dark weizen; probably my best so far.

Big offwhite lasting head. Hazy opaque orangey body. Milky ash and carrot aroma with wheaty banana notes. Dry-sweetish milky banana and carrot taste with ashy notes. Mid-bodied. Rounded mouthfeel. Dry ashy milky soy sauce aftertaste. Nice, drinkable, unusual. I like it. (0.5l bottle, from some supermarket in Kiel.)

Medium head, lightish brown colour. Cool, malty aroma, with faint fruitiness. Full, harmonic, well-rounded malt taste with faint hints of roastiness. Aftertaste is mostly hops and faint roastiness, somewhat dry. A good session beer, but not too interesting.

Largish finely laced head. Amber, whisky-like colour. Aroma is dense caramelly malts with notes of dried fruit and straw, with some alcohol. Powerful malty caramelly strawberry taste with alcohol and straw notes. Clean and harmonic, with considerable alcohol heat. Dry straw and caramel aftertaste. Smooth and quite balanced. Full-bodied. Very good for such a strong beer. (0.33l bottle at Hagleite, Kulmbach, originally. Rerated from 0.1l taster from bottle at EBF '08.)

Smallish off-white head, which subsides. Dark mahogany red body. Aroma is malty, with hints of alcohol and roastiness. Taste is dark and subtle, somewhat roasty, giving way to deep toffee-like sweetness and finally alcohol heat balanced by faint hop bitterness. A very good, and very interesting beer. I wouldn't have that many at once (for more than one reason :), but very good.

Smallish white fine-bubbled head over dark mahogany body. Lovely sweet, smoky flowery aroma with hop notes. Taste is very like the smell, but with slightly more pronounced smokiness. The finish is nicely rounded, but mostly a simple fading. A very good ale; strong, interesting taste, yet easily drinkable. (0.5l bottle, self-poured in lager glass.)

Small, dark-beige head; very dark, nearly opaque red-black body. Deep, sweet licorice aroma with hints of hops. Taste is strong, roasty, and smooth, with a nice, bitter finish. A good porter, but not as  complex as I might wish. Very drinkable, though. (0.33l bottle self-poured in lager glass.)

Big beige head, very fine foam. Dark red colour. Sourish, mahogany aroma. Taste heavy, like a dark Belgian, but with hints of something sourish, mahogany-like. Very good, but more sippable than drinkable.

500 ml can. Pours a dark reddish brown, medium head. Unremarkable appearance. Aroma is faint; vague hints of malts and spice. Taste is not very powerful, mostly malts and a hint of roastiness, somewhat sweet. The aftertaste is where it happens, the taste goes somewhat dry and more intense, but even that isn’t too heavy. My impression is that Mack is trying to introduce non-lager beer to their customers without scaring them off with something wild. If so, this might just work, or they might not be able to tell the difference between this and Norwegian bayer. Anyway, the beer is nice, drinkable, and unexciting.

500ml can. Pours a hazy light orange, with slight yeast, and small head. Can makes it difficult to get the yeast into the beer, so hefeweizen in a can is clearly not a great idea. Aroma is fainly fruity and banana-like. Taste is thin, somewhat sourish, with slight fruity and spicy notes. Pleasant, easy to drink, but not very remarkable. Probably a good way to introduce Norwegians unfamiliar with weizen to the style.

Darkish brown in colour, smallish lacy head. Aroma is mostly malts. Taste is surprisingly light, mostly malts again, but with a slightly roast background. Very similar to the Nøgne Ø brown ale. Overall, a nicely drinkable and pleasant beer, if perhaps not too exciting. Probably a good way to introduce non-beer-geeks to quality beer.

Golden colour, smallish, lacy head. Lovely aroma of what appears to be American hops. Taste is much like the aroma, but with an added crisp taste of malts. Reminds me of a lighter version of Goose Island IPA.  The overall impression is very nice indeed. Also very drinkable, so you can safely buy lots of this.

Bottle. Best-before jan 2005, tasted july 2005. Medium off-white head, very dark red colour. Light roasted, hoppy nose. Subtle taste; some malts, some burntness, dry hoppy finish. A relatively light beer, taste-wise; unremarkable, but quite good.

Dark orange, initially large creamy head, which quickly subsides. Nose like many pale ales, but fruitier. Taste full of malts, but with a fruity body, followed by a deliciously sharp, bitter aftertaste with hints of spice. Overall, very nice for an English pale ale; more taste than what is usual.

Bottled. Dark cloudy orange with a relatively small head. Vaguely citrusy and yeasty aroma. Slightly thin-bodied taste of yeast and wheat malts, yielding to a surprisingly bitter hop taste  with some sourness at the end. Unusual, somewhat interesting, and quite good.

Canned. Bronze colour. Vague maltiness with slight bitterness. Not much taste, and in the end the bitterness dominates. Why they bother brewing this for easter is a mystery, really, given that the only thing that makes it stand out in any way at all is the bright yellow colour of the can.
Medium head, dark orange colour. Malty nose with powerful hop aroma. Dry malty, hoppy body, with both hops and malts lingering long into the aftertaste. Absolutely lovely!

Medium head, dark brown colour. Lovely sweet, malty smell of spice. Taste rather like the smell, with burnt notes and fruitiness. Aftertaste has slight hops bitterness, and more burntness. Very nice! No humbug about this one.

Cloudy orange, medium head. Enormous lovely hop aroma of citrus and flowers. Deep, powerful initial taste, followed by heavy bitterness that lingers. Fantastic! A beer to savour, and IMHO the best Norwegian beer currently available.

(500 ml bottle, purchased in a pub after the owner learned I was interested in beer. Had it twice.)  Cloudy, dark orange, substantial head. Oily mouthfeel. Less aroma and taste than the Nøgne Ø IPA. Powerful, heavy taste, with substantial bitterness. The 80 IBU are quite well hidden, and overall I'm somewhat disappointed. I had enormous expectations for this beer after the Nøgne Ø IPA, so even if I was disappointed this remains a very good beer.
